  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages:\n- 1970 Bank Secrecy Act (USA)\n- First international recognition of money laundering as a criminal activity\n- Initial reporting requirements for financial institutions\n\n2. 1980s Developments:\n- United Nations Convention against Illicit Drug Trafficking (1988)\n- Increased focus on tracking drug-related financial crimes\n- Growing international cooperation\n\n3. 1990s Expansion:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Developed comprehensive anti-money laundering (AML) recommendations\n- More stringent reporting and due diligence requirements\n\n4. Post-9/11 Legislation:\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced financial surveillance\n- Expanded definition of money laundering\n- Stronger counter-terrorism financing measures\n\n5. Recent Trends:\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Cryptocurrency regulation\n- Beneficial ownership transparency\n- Stricter know-your-customer (KYC) protocols\n- International information sharing mechanisms\n\n6. Emerging Focus:\n- Blockchain and cryptocurrency tracking\n- Advanced technological solutions\n- Cross-border regulatory collaboration\n\nThe legislation continues to adapt to evolving financial technologies and criminal methods.",
